# Simple Web Stack Explanation

Many websites run on a simple infrastructure using a single server. Here, we design a server hosting a website accessible via www.foobar.com

## Step 1: User Request

When a user visits www.foobar.com
their browser sends an HTTP/HTTPS request. The DNS resolves the domain to the server IP 8.8.8.8, pointing to our server.

## Step 2: Server Components

### The server contains:

Web Server (Nginx) – receives requests, serves static files, forwards dynamic requests to the application server.

Application Server – executes application code (PHP, Python, Node.js) and generates dynamic responses.

Application Files / Codebase – contains the code and assets used by the application server.

Database (MySQL) – stores data like users, posts, and comments for the application.

## Step 3: Roles Explained

Server: provides services to clients over a network.

Domain Name: translates human-readable addresses into IPs.

DNS Record (www): an A record pointing to the server’s IP.

Web Server: handles incoming requests and serves content.

Application Server: runs business logic and dynamic content generation.

Database: stores structured application data.

Communication: uses HTTP/HTTPS between the server and the user’s browser.

## Step 4: Issues

SPOF (Single Point of Failure): if the server fails, the site is offline.

Downtime During Maintenance: restarting the server or deploying new code causes temporary unavailability.

Scalability Limitations: a single server cannot handle high traffic; performance may degrade.

## Step 5: Summary

This single-server infrastructure is simple and low-cost, suitable for small sites, but it is not fault-tolerant and cannot scale easily. For larger traffic or high availability, multiple servers or distributed architectures are required.

